Class FrictionInversion

Allows to perform anisotopic friction and cohesion distribution inversion using multiple type of dataset on complex fault geometries.

example
const model = new arch.Model()
// --> add surface discontinuities
// --> setup surface boundary conditions and values

const algo = new arch.FrictionInversion(model)
algo.setRemote( remoteFromStressInversion )
algo.setBurgers( displFromSlipInversion )
algo.run()

const friction = algo.getDipFriction()

  • dipFriction(): Vectord

  • Get the computed friction distribution along the dip axis

influences

  • influences(): Vectord

  • For convenience, return the residual tractions from the imposed burger vectors

    Returns Vectord

run

  • run(): void
  • brief

    Run the friction inversion on the provided model using the remote stress and burgers

    Returns void

setBurgers

  • setBurgers(burgers: Vectord): void

  • Set the displacement on triangular elements making the faults. These burgers come from, for example, SlipInversion.

    Parameters

    • burgers: Vectord

    Returns void

setRemote

  • setRemote(remote: UserRemote): void

  • Set the estimated far field stress. This come from stress inversion using the same model and data as for SlipInversion.

    see

    setBurgers

    Parameters

    • remote: UserRemote

    Returns void

strikeFriction

  • strikeFriction(): Vectord

  • Get the computed friction distribution along the strike axis. If anisotropy was set to false, dipFriction and strikeFriction return the same array.

    Returns Vectord

tractions

  • tractions(): Vectord

  • For convenience, return the remote tractions

    Returns Vectord

useAnisotropy

  • useAnisotropy(u: boolean): void

  • If the algo have to perform the inversion along the dip and strike axis.

    default

    false

    Parameters

    • u: boolean

      True to use anisotropy

    Returns void
